<paragraph id="8BEC3695FFD0FF8CB5B9FBFFFB99FED7" blockId="28.[189,1398,1050,1112]" lastBlockId="30.[189,1399,265,362]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="104" pageId="28" pageNumber="102">
The female of this species is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C534D16FFD0FF8EB7FEFBFFFB9EFB89" authority="Nurse, 1903" authorityName="Nurse" authorityYear="1903" box="[762,1046,1050,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tantalus">
<emphasis id="B927EA87FFD0FF8EB7FEFBFFFCF1FB89" box="[762,889,1050,1076]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="102">S. tantalus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC24B64FFD0FF8EB687FBFFFB9EFB89" author="Nurse C. G." box="[899,1046,1050,1076]" pageId="28" pageNumber="102" pagination="528 - 549" refId="ref18735" refString="Nurse C. G. 1903. New species of Indian aculeate Hymenoptera. Annals and Magazine of Natural History Series 7 11: 393 - 403, 511 - 526, 528 - 549. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930308678811" type="journal article" year="1903">Nurse, 1903</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
owing to a similar structure, sculpture and coloration of the body, but it differs from this species by having a more densely punctate mesoscutum, with the punctures separated by 1–2 puncture diameters (vs 2–5), and the pygidial plate as wide as the metabasitarsus (vs 0.8). Both these species are close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C534D16FFD2FF8CB6F6FEC8FAAFFEFB" authority="Thomson, 1870" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1870" box="[1010,1319,300,327]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis id="B927EA87FFD2FF8CB6F6FEC8FBEFFEFB" box="[1010,1127,301,327]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="104">S. crassus</emphasis>
Thomson, 1870
</taxonomicName>
by the strongly enlarged metafemur, but it differs by the entirely red metasoma.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
